üíª Technical Overview: HeatEs - Hotspots in Spain
Project Goal
HeatEs is an application designed to visualize anonymous, aggregated risk signals in Spain as a heatmap. Its primary goal is to provide a simple, privacy-focused tool for informational and preventative purposes, without exposing individual data.

Core Architecture
The project is structured into three main components:

Data Ingestion & Processing (ETL): This is an automated, scheduled process that collects data from various open and moderated community sources.

Data Normalization: Raw data is cleaned and standardized.

Geocoding: Data is converted into geographical coordinates.

Spatial Aggregation: Raw signals are aggregated into a hexagonal grid using H3 cells. This process uses thresholds to prevent individual events from standing out, ensuring a high level of anonymity.

Temporal Decaying: More recent data is given more weight to ensure the heatmap reflects the current situation.

Data Service (API): This backend service is responsible for serving the aggregated data.

It provides the H3 cells and their corresponding aggregated values to the frontend.

Data is served in a format that allows the frontend to render the heatmap layer efficiently.

Frontend (UI): This is the user-facing application that visualizes the data.

Base Map: A clean, neutral grey map is used to minimize distractions.

Heatmap Layer: The application overlays a heatmap on the base map. This layer is dynamically generated and re-calculated with high quality as the user zooms and pans, ensuring a crisp visual representation.

Temporal Filters: Users can select different time windows (1 day, 1 month, 1 year) to view the data.

Vector Tiles: The heatmap data is likely rendered using vector tiles to ensure smooth performance and high-quality visuals at different zoom levels.

Key Technical Features
Privacy-First Aggregation:

Uses H3 (Hierarchical, Hexagonal, and High-Resolution) geospatial indexing system for spatial aggregation. This ensures that no individual points are visible.

Includes thresholds to prevent cells with a low number of events from being displayed, further enhancing privacy.

The system only shows aggregated data, never individual, identifiable information.

Scalable & Performant Visualization:

The heatmap layer is not a static image. The 'heat' is re-calculated based on the zoom level, providing a continuous and refined visualization.

The use of vector tiles and zoom-based aggregation ensures smooth and high-quality rendering without performance issues.

Automated Data Pipeline:

An automated ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) process is in place to collect, normalize, geocode, and aggregate data from sources automatically.

The system includes logic for duplicate control and filtering out "weak" signals.

Planned Future Features (Roadmap)
AI Agent: A planned feature to use an AI agent to assist in the verification and updating of data by navigating public sources in a controlled manner.

Quality Metrics: Development of metrics to measure data quality, including coverage, freshness, and stability.

"Lite" Mode: A simplified version of the application for use on less powerful devices.

Local Setup & Installation
For developers, the project can be run locally:

Clone the Repository: Get the project code from the repository.

Configuration: Create a .env configuration file containing the necessary API keys for the base map and the data endpoints.

Run Services:

Start the frontend user interface.

Start the data service (API).

Access: Open the application in your web browser.

A step-by-step guide is maintained in the project's documentation at /docs/instalacion_local.md.

This technical summary is based on the details provided in the original text and is designed to provide a clear overview for anyone interested in the project's architecture and inner workings.







